# Usage
These are some examples. For more information, read the [[manpage|usage]]

## Convert files

<pre>$ <b>dir2ogg foo.mp3</b> # <em>one file...</em>
$ <b>dir2ogg -t foo.mp3</b> # <em>one file (keep quality, only for mp3)...</em>
$ <b>dir2ogg foo.mp3 bar.m4a baz.wma qux.wav</b> # <em>multiple files...</em>
</pre>

## Converting directories

<pre>$ <b>dir2ogg -d /path/to/mp3directory</b> # <em>single directory...</em>
$ <b>dir2ogg /path/to/mp3directory</b> # <em>single directory..., same as previous one.</em>
$ <b>dir2ogg -r /path/to/mp3directory</b> # <em>single directory (and subdirs)...</em>
$ <b>dir2ogg -d /path/1/ /path/2 /path/3</b> # <em>multiple directories...</em>
$ <b>dir2ogg -r /path/1/ /path/2 /path/3</b> # <em>recursive...</em></pre>

## Converting Audio CDs

<pre>$ <b>dir2ogg -c</b> # <em>convert cd in /dev/cdrom</em>
$ <b>dir2ogg -c /dev/cdrom1</b> # <em>convert cd in /dev/cdrom1</em></pre>

# Warning
_"Converting from MP3 or M4A to OGG is a conversion between two lossy formats. This is fine if you just want to free up some disk space, but if you're a hard-core audiophile you may be disappointed. I really can't notice a difference in quality with 'naked' ears myself. You might want to do your conversion, then compare with the original before erasing them."_ - Darren Kirby, first dir2ogg developer
